[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 summary: "A practical guide to building task harnesses and
 how they differ from evaluation and agent harnesses (informed by the reference
d talk)."[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (55.81256pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 Task harnesses are the scaffolding that turn a high-level 
engineering question—
 []


Overfull \hbox (1263.0498pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 "Can this system finish a real task?"—into reproducible, deb
uggable experiments. This post explains what "Task Harness Engineering" means, 
how it differs from Eval harnesses (benchmarks) and Agent harnesses (integratio
n + environment tests), and practical recommendations for building one.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (394.98868pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 [![Harness Engineering talk (YouTube)](https://img.youtube
.com/vi/C_GG5g38vLU/hqdefault.jpg)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C_GG5g38vLU
)[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (234.02377pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 Source: Harness Engineering (YouTube), referenced for conc
eptual framing and examples (video id: C_GG5g38vLU).[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (912.37613pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - A harness is code and infra that runs a task, measures o
utcomes, and records what happened. Harnesses range from small unit-test-like r
unners to complex environment orchestrators that start services, browsers, or V
M sandboxes.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (257.01877pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Goal: exercise an agent or system with realistic tasks t
hat capture the operational surface area you care about.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (584.69745pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Characteristics: stateful, often non-deterministic, reli
ant on external systems or realistic mocks, and focused on end-to-end success r
ather than a single scalar metric.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (728.41617pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Example tasks: finish a multi-step research workflow, tr
iage a bug in a real repo, navigate a web app and complete a purchase flow, or 
orchestrate tools to solve a programming prompt with tests.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (394.98872pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Measurements: success/failure, retries, time-to-completi
on, observability traces, logs, and qualitative artifacts (replays/screenshots)
.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (147.79254pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Eval harnesses run static, dataset-driven evaluations (d
atasets, metrics, automated scorers).[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (435.22998pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Characteristics: deterministic or quasi-deterministic, h
igh throughput, designed to compute reproducible aggregates (accuracy, F1, BLEU
, etc.).[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (630.68744pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Weaknesses vs Task Harness: lower realism (benchmarks ar
e proxies), brittle to specification differences, and limited visibility into l
ong-horizon or environment-level failures.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (630.68744pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Agent harnesses focus on agents interacting with environ
ments (simulated worlds, browsers, shells, APIs) and on integration points: too
l calls, state persistence, safety checks.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (239.77252pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Characteristics: emphasizes sandboxing, step-level instr
umentation, and emergent behaviors across many steps.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (831.89365pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Overlap with Task Harness: agent harnesses are often the
 runtime that executes task harnesses when the subject is an agent; agent harne
sses add concerns like action validation, safety guards, and tool interfaces.[]
 
 []


Overfull \hbox (257.01877pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Realism: Task >> Eval. Agent harness sits between and of
ten provides the runtime for tasks that exercise agents.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (780.1549pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Metrics: Eval focuses on aggregated scalars; Task harnes
ses capture a richer set (end-to-end success, observability, human judgments). 
Agent harnesses must capture both step-level and end-to-end signals.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (831.89365pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Infrastructure: Task harnesses require orchestration of 
real or high-fidelity mocks (browsers, CLIs, repos). Eval harnesses only need f
ast scoring pipelines. Agent harnesses require safe sandboxes and tool shims.[]
 
 []


Overfull \hbox (205.28003pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Instrumentation-first: log inputs, decisions, tool calls
, and environment responses. Design for replay.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (326.00375pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Replayability: capture transcripts and environment snaps
hots so failed runs can be replayed deterministically when possible.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (366.245pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Tasks that "fight back": design tasks that surface edge 
cases, race conditions, and adversarial inputs instead of only happy paths.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (705.42117pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Hybrid approach: use eval harnesses for fast filtering, 
then escalate promising models to task harnesses for realism tests, and run age
nt harnesses in parallel to validate tool integrations.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (394.98874pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Isolation and safety: run untrusted code in sandboxes; f
or web/OS interaction prefer ephemeral VMs/containers and recorded interactions
.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (320.255pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Observability and triage: attach lightweight traces (req
uest ids, timestamps) to link model internals to external failures.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (90.30505pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Use Eval harness when you need fast, repeatable comparis
ons during model iteration.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (268.51627pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Use Task harness when your priority is real-world behavi
or, end-to-end failure modes, or human-facing UX outcomes.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (222.52628pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Use Agent harness when validating tool use, stateful int
eractions, or safety boundaries across many steps.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (1774.68845pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 Task Harness Engineering complements, not replaces, eval a
nd agent harnesses. The right pipeline uses them together: evaluate cheaply, va
lidate realistically, and instrument deeply. Start with a minimal task harness 
for the most critical user journeys, make reproducible recordings, and iterate:
 increase realism until the harness meaningfully predicts production failure mo
des.[] 
 []


Overfull \hbox (211.02876pt too wide) in paragraph at lines 71--71
[]\TU/lmtt/m/n/10.95 - Video source (conceptual reference): https://www.youtube
.com/watch?v=C_GG5g38vLU (video id: C_GG5g38vLU)[] 
 []


